Shouldn't it be:

proxyVar.Proxy.MakeAnOperationCall();

?

I like the following construct a bit better:

public static void Using<T>(Action<T> action) where T : ICommunicationObject, IDisposable, new()
{
    var service = new T();

    bool success = false;
    try
    {
        action(service);
        service.Close();
        success = true;
    }
    finally
    {
        if (!success)
        {
            service.Abort();
        }
    }
}

which you can use:

ServiceCall.Using<FooClient>(service =&gt;
{
    service.DoStuff();
});

While it does create a delegate which might be a bit confusing to a junior to debug (having to step into it as opposed to over it), the code feels a bit nicer.</FooClient></T></T>
